Kerberoasting via Rubeus or Impacket Tool Execution
In this threat hunting scenario, we searched for evidence of Kerberoasting attacks by monitoring the execution of well-known offensive tools such as Rubeus and Impacket (e.g., GetST, GetTGT, asktgs), as well as command-line arguments associated with requesting Kerberos service tickets using RC4 (ETYPE-23) encryption. The hunt focused on identifying attempts to obtain service tickets that could later be cracked offline to recover service account passwords.

Kerberoasting is a common post-compromise technique used by attackers after gaining access to an Active Directory environment. Successfully cracking a privileged service account password can enable privilege escalation, lateral movement, persistence, and ultimately compromise of the entire domain.

Sentinel One Query:
/* Kerberoasting Detection — Rubeus / Impacket process-level telemetry
 * SentinelOne EDR does not ingest Windows Security Event Logs (e.g., Event ID 4769
 * for ETYPE 23 RC4 ticket requests). The RC4/ETYPE-23 signal is approximated via
 * command-line arguments passed to known Kerberoasting tooling.
 */
event.type = "Process Creation"
AND (
    // Rubeus binary execution (any parent)
    tgt.process.name in:anycase ("Rubeus.exe")
    OR
    // Rubeus Kerberoasting sub-commands
    tgt.process.cmdline contains:matchcase "kerberoast"
    OR
    // Impacket GetST / GetTGT / asktgs scripts (python or compiled)
    tgt.process.cmdline contains:matchcase "GetST"
    OR
    tgt.process.cmdline contains:matchcase "GetTGT"
    OR
    tgt.process.cmdline contains:matchcase "asktgs"
    OR
    // RC4 downgrade flag explicitly passed to tooling
    tgt.process.cmdline contains ("/rc4", "-rc4", "--rc4", "rc4opsec", "etype 23", "etype:23", "-etype 23")
)
// Exclude known signed Microsoft and Kerberos management binaries
AND NOT (
    tgt.process.publisher in:anycase (
        "Microsoft Corporation",
        "Microsoft Windows"
    )
)
// Exclude dedicated admin hosts if applicable
AND NOT (endpoint.name matches "(?i)^(DC|PKI|ADFS)-")
| columns
    endpoint.name,
    endpoint.os,
    src.process.name,
    src.process.cmdline,
    src.process.user,
    tgt.process.name,
    tgt.process.cmdline,
    tgt.process.image.path,
    tgt.process.signedStatus,
    tgt.process.publisher
| sort -timestamp
